&bull; <b>	Allow yourself to process your emotions: </b> Give yourself permission to feel and acknowledge your emotions. It's normal to experience a range of emotions such as shock, fear, anger, sadness, or confusion. Allow yourself time and space to grieve and process what has happened.<br><br>
&bull; <b> 	Reach out for support: </b> Seek support from trusted friends, family members, or professionals. Talk to someone who can provide a listening ear, empathy, and understanding. Consider reaching out to a therapist or counselor trained in trauma to help you navigate the healing process.<br><br>
&bull; <b> 	Practice self-care: </b> Prioritize self-care activities that promote your physical, mental, and emotional well-being. Engage in activities that bring you comfort, such as exercise, spending time in nature, practicing relaxation techniques, journaling, or pursuing hobbies.<br><br>
&bull; <b> 	Maintain a routine: </b> Establishing a routine can provide a sense of stability and normalcy in the aftermath of a traumatic event. Stick to regular sleep patterns, mealtimes, and engage in daily activities that give structure to your day.<br><br>
&bull; <b> 	Seek professional help: </b> If you find that your symptoms persist, worsen, or interfere with your daily life, consider seeking professional help from a therapist or counselor. They can provide specialized support and guide you through the healing process.<br><br>
&bull; <b> 	Practice grounding techniques: </b> Grounding techniques can help you feel more present and centered when you experience distressing thoughts or emotions. Examples include deep breathing exercises, focusing on your senses, or engaging in activities that require concentration.<br><br>
&bull; <b> 	Limit exposure to triggers: </b> Be mindful of situations, people, or reminders that trigger distressing memories or emotions related to the traumatic event. It's okay to set boundaries and limit your exposure to such triggers, especially during the early stages of healing.<br><br>
